Five Truths Concerning Terrorism
SÃO PAULO – American policy is hostage to terrorism.
In December 2015, polls indicated that one in six Americans, or approximately 16% of the population, now placed terrorism at the top of the country's problems – an increase of 3% in a month.
Since ten years, never have so many Americans been so concerned about terrorism, even though their number is still far below the 46% recorded the day after the September 11, 2001, attacks.
The consequences of this shift in public opinion became most apparent during the Republican primary for the presidential election.
The candidacy of Donald Trump, whose anti-Muslim rhetoric is particularly fiery (if not incendiary), undoubtedly benefited from it.
Some politicians justify speaking of the battle against terrorism as the "Third World War."
Terrorism is a problem for the United States, as shown by the San Bernardino attack in California last December.
But whose presidential candidates, just like some media outlets, followers of the old adage "if it bleeds, it leads," have exaggerated the scale.
To place terrorism in its true perspective, Americans should – like others – keep the following considerations in mind:
Terrorism is a kind of theater.
The terrorists are more concerned with capturing attention and dominating political headlines than with the number, in itself, of their victims.
The Islamic State (IS) takes great care with its staging.
The brutal beheadings broadcasted on social media are intended to destabilize and shock – and therefore to monopolize attention.
Exaggerating their consequences and making headlines with every terrorist act is playing into the terrorists' hands.
Terrorism is not the most serious threat facing populations in developed countries.
Terrorism kills far less than road accidents or smoking.
From this perspective, terrorism is not even a real threat – neither major nor minor.
One is more likely to be struck by lightning than killed by a terrorist.
The probability that an American citizen is assassinated by a terrorist, according to experts, is one in 3.5 million.
Americans are more likely to die in their bathtub (one in 950,000), from a domestic appliance accident (one in 1.5 million), from a deer or moose crossing the road (one in 2 million), or in a commercial airplane crash (one in 2.9 million).
Six thousand Americans die every year while driving by texting or talking on their cell phones.
This is several hundred times the number of those who die from terrorism.
Radical Islamic terrorism kills fewer Americans than attacks carried out by disgruntled employees or mass shootings on campuses or in schools.
Terrorism is not the Third World War.
Global terrorism is not new.
It often takes a generation to extinguish a terrorist surge.
At the beginning of the 20th century, the anarchist movement killed a number of heads of state in the name of utopian ideals.
During the 1960s and 1970s, the Red Brigades and the Red Army Fraction, emerging from the "autonomous" left, diverted airplanes outside national borders and kidnapped or killed business leaders or political figures (but also ordinary citizens).
Today's jihadist extremists are an old political phenomenon dressed in religious garb.
Many of their leaders are not fundamentalists in the traditional sense, but people whose identities have been destroyed by globalization, seeking meaning in the imagined and pure community of an Islamic caliphate.
It will take time and effort to defeat them, but the restrictive nature of the IS limits its appeal.
Its sectarian attacks already prevent it from addressing all Muslims, let alone Hindus, Christians, or other believers.
The IS will ultimately be defeated, just as previous transnational terrorist movements have been.
Terrorism is like judo.
The weaker of the two adversaries uses the strength of the stronger to defeat him.
No terrorist organization has the power of a state, and few terrorist movements have managed to overthrow one.
But if they manage to shock and provoke enough citizens of a state to push them into futile actions, they may hope to gain the upper hand.
In 2001, Al-Qaeda managed to draw Americans into Afghanistan.
The Islamic State emerged from the ruins of the U.S.-led invasion of Iraq, which followed the intervention in Afghanistan.
To defeat terrorism, one needs smart power.
Smart power is capable of combining the coercive power (hard power) of the military and police with the influence power (soft power) of seduction and persuasion.
Soft power is also necessary if one wants to immunize those on the periphery and who the irreconcilables seek to recruit.
That is why the attention given to the narrative of events and the way U.S. actions are commented on social media is as important and necessary as precision air strikes.
The rhetoric of confrontation, which points fingers at Muslims and alienates the good will that would allow us to obtain crucial information, puts us all in danger.
That is why the anti-Islam stance of some current presidential candidates is so counterproductive.
The terrorist issue is serious, and it deserves to be placed among the priorities of our intelligence and police services, our armed forces, and our diplomacy.
It constitutes an important factor in our foreign policy.
And it is essential to keep weapons of mass destruction out of the reach of terrorists.
But we must not fall into the trap set by the terrorists.
Let us not fill the theater where the actions of brutes and hoodlums take place.
If we surrender the great stage of our public discourse to them, we will weaken the quality of our civic life and reveal our priorities.
Our strength would then be used against us.
